{
  "query": "What are the benefits for butterflies and moths of reducing or eliminating chemical inputs on farmland?",
  "relevant_summary": "Reducing or eliminating chemical inputs on farmland provides significant benefits for butterflies and moths. Studies found that areas managed with less frequent, reduced, or no pesticide, herbicide, fertilizer, or unspecified chemical inputs had greater species richness of adult butterflies and moths, or caterpillars, compared to areas with more frequent or conventional chemical applications (action 3897). Similarly, arable field margins and rice field banks that were not sprayed with herbicides like glyphosate had greater species richness and higher abundance of butterflies than sprayed areas (action 3896). Converting to organic farming also showed benefits, with seven of eleven studies finding that organic farms had greater species richness and abundance of butterflies and moths than conventionally managed farms (action 3907). These benefits included not only overall increases in butterfly and moth populations, but also specific species preferences for unfertilized or lightly fertilized grasslands over heavily fertilized ones.",
