{
  "query": "What are some evidence-based alternatives to prescribed burning for managing disturbance in forests to benefit butterflies?",
  "relevant_summary": "Evidence-based alternatives to prescribed burning for managing forest disturbance to benefit butterflies include: (1) Thinning trees within forests - studies in the USA and Finland found that coniferous woodland which had been thinned, along with other management practices, had greater species richness and abundance of butterflies compared to unmanaged woodland. (2) Clearing or opening patches in forests - 14 studies across multiple countries found that cleared patches had greater species richness and abundance of butterflies than unmanaged patches or closed canopy forest, benefiting species such as chequered blue, woodland brown, high brown fritillary and small pearl-bordered fritillary. (3) Coppicing woodland - 10 studies found that coppiced woodland had higher abundance of butterflies generally, and species such as heath fritillary specifically, compared to unmanaged woodland, with optimal benefits occurring 2-7 years after coppicing. (4) Creating young plantations within mature woodland - one UK study found that woodlands with larger areas of young plantations helped pearl-bordered fritillary and small pearl-bordered fritillary populations persist longer than in mature woodland.",
