{
  "query": "What does the evidence show about the timeframe for butterfly and moth population response to woodland coppicing or clearing?",
  "relevant_summary": "The evidence shows that butterfly and moth populations respond to woodland coppicing and clearing over various timeframes. For coppicing, studies found that abundance was higher in woodland coppiced 2-4 years ago compared to older coppice (5-11 years or >15 years). One study found that woodland coppiced 2 years ago had greater butterfly species richness than woodland coppiced >15 years ago. For clearing patches in forests, one study found that patches cleared 2-4 years ago had greater abundance of heath fritillary butterflies than patches cleared 7-11 years ago or patches in their first year after clearance. Another study reported that butterfly species richness declined over the first three years after clearing, but abundance initially increased before declining. The evidence suggests that populations typically respond positively 2-4 years after management, but responses can vary by species and decline as vegetation ages beyond this timeframe.",
  "action_ids": [
    "3939",
    "3938"
  ]
}

